SIMPLE: enlarge
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enlarge
<hw>En*large"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Enlarged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Enlarging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>enlargier</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + F.
<ets>large</ets> wide. See <er>Large</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
make larger; to increase in quantity or dimensions; to extend in limits;
to magnify; <as>as, the body is <ex>enlarged</ex> by nutrition; to
<ex>enlarge</ex> one's house.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>enlarge</qex> their possessions of land.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To increase the capacity of; to expand; to give free
scope or greater scope to; also, to dilate, as with joy, affection, and
the like; <as>as, knowledge <ex>enlarges</ex> the mind</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O ye Corinthians, our . . . heart is <qex>enlarged</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Cor. vi. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To set at large or set free.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will <qex>enlarge</qex> us from all restraints.</q>
<rj><qau>Barrow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Enlarging hammer</b></col>, <cd>a hammer with a slightly
rounded face of large diameter; -- used by gold beaters.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <mcol><col><b>To enlarge an order</b></col>
<it>or</it> <col><b>To enlarge a rule</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<cd>to extend the time for complying with it.</cd> <au>Abbott.</au> --
<col><b>To enlarge one's self</b></col>, <cd>to give free vent to
speech; to spread out discourse.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧They <xex>enlarged</xex>
themselves on this subject.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Clarendon.</au> -- <col><b>To
enlarge the heart</b></col>, <cd>to make free, liberal, and
charitable.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To increase; extend; expand; spread; amplify;
augment; magnify. See <er>Increase</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enlarge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Enlarge
<hw>En*large"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow large or
larger; to be further extended; to expand; <as>as, a plant
<ex>enlarges</ex> by growth; an estate <ex>enlarges</ex> by good
management; a volume of air <ex>enlarges</ex> by
rarefaction.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To speak or write at length; to be diffuse in
speaking or writing; to expatiate; to dilate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>enlarge</qex> upon this theme.</q> <rj><qau>M.
Arnold.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To get more astern or parallel
with the vessel's course; to draw aft; -- said of the wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enlarged</ent>⟦br⟧
